\begin_layout Standard
Given the structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, we can write the operator as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
C_{0} & C_{1}^{\dagger}\\
C_{1} & -C_{0}\\
 &  & C_{2} & C_{3}^{\dagger}\\
 &  & C_{3} & -C_{2}
\end{array}\right)\,,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C_{0} & =i\left(P_{12}-P_{03}\right)\\
C_{1} & =\left(P_{13}+P_{02}\right)+i\left(P_{23}-P_{01}\right)\\
C_{2} & =i\left(P_{12}+P_{03}\right)\\
C_{3} & =\left(P_{13}-P_{02}\right)+i\left(P_{23}+P_{01}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full local part of the Dirac matrix is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\left(\frac{1}{2\kappa}+i\mu\gamma_{5}\right)+T\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability distribution contains a term
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det Q\propto\det M=\exp-S\,,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=-\sum_{x}\ln\det M\left(x\right)\:.
\]

\end_inset


